		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>As a fan, not a student of McCourt, and as a descendant  in this country, of Irish parents, what amazed me was the reaction of some Irish Americans to Angelas Ashes.  They would not read past the first 15 pages because they became too ashamed &#8211; it  hit too close to home  They could see where McCourt was headed with his writing.</p>
<p>I was/am grateful and proud of his telling of the poverty,  ignorance,  and hard heartedness of those who could have helped more,  but did not.</p>
<p>Now I wonder as I read books about other countries and cultures where poverty, ignorance and religious and governmental oppression  abounds or has in the recent past, &#8211; are the sons and daughters of these countries who live in the US now, ashamed or grateful for the telling of the real story.</p>
<p>If they are ashamed, I will be sensitive and courteous.  If they deny the existence of the problems written about, I will be sorry and disgusted.</p>
<p>Thank you Frank for giving us such a wonderful story, told with so much humor and hope.</p>

		</div>
